      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take calcium with vitamin D?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. Vitamin D is essential for calcium absorption in the intestine. Without adequate vitamin D, you absorb only 10-15% of dietary calcium. With sufficient vitamin D, absorption increases to 30-40%. Most experts recommend 600-2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily alongside calcium supplementation. Many calcium gummies include vitamin D3 in the formula, which is a significant advantage. If your calcium gummy does not contain vitamin D, take a separate vitamin D3 supplement with it.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can calcium gummies cause kidney stones?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The relationship between calcium supplementation and kidney stones is nuanced. Excessive supplemental calcium (above 2,000mg/day total from diet + supplements) may increase kidney stone risk in some individuals. However, adequate calcium intake from food actually reduces kidney stone risk by binding oxalate in the gut. The key is moderation: do not exceed 500-600mg of supplemental calcium per day, take it with meals, stay well hydrated, and avoid combining with high oxalate foods. People with a history of calcium oxalate kidney stones should consult their physician.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why are calcium gummies lower dose than calcium pills?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Calcium is a bulky mineral. Delivering 500mg of calcium carbonate in pill form requires a large tablet, and compressing it into a gummy format is even more challenging. Most calcium gummies contain 200-500mg per serving (typically 2-3 gummies) because higher doses would make the gummies impractically large or require eating 4-6 gummies per serving. This is why calcium gummies work best as a dietary supplement rather than a sole calcium source.' },
