    <h2 id="why-calcium">Why Calcium Supplementation Matters for Bone Health</h2>

    <p>Calcium is the structural foundation of the skeletal system. Your bones contain 99% of the body's total calcium stores, and bone tissue is continuously remodeled throughout life — old bone is broken down (resorption) and new bone is deposited (formation). When dietary calcium intake is insufficient, the body pulls calcium from bones to maintain critical blood calcium levels for nerve signaling, muscle contraction, and heart rhythm. Over years and decades, this net calcium withdrawal leads to decreased bone density, osteopenia, and eventually osteoporosis.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">43%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of American adults do not consume adequate calcium through diet alone, according to the National Institutes of Health. <strong>Women over 50 and men over 70 are at highest risk</strong> for calcium-related bone density loss — and are the populations least likely to meet daily requirements through food.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The gummy format presents a genuine formulation challenge for calcium: it is a bulky mineral that cannot be compressed as easily into gummies as vitamins can. Most calcium gummies deliver 200-500mg per serving — meaningful supplementation, but not a complete daily dose. This makes calcium gummies ideal for bridging the gap between dietary intake and the 1,000-1,200mg daily recommendation, rather than serving as a sole calcium source. The key advantage of gummies over tablets is compliance: calcium tablets are notoriously large and difficult to swallow, and many people abandon them within months. Gummies solve this problem entirely.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Calcium Carbonate</strong>
        <p>Contains 40% elemental calcium — the highest concentration of any form. Requires stomach acid for absorption, so take with food. Most common and affordable form. May cause bloating or constipation at higher doses. Found in most mainstream calcium gummies.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Calcium Citrate</strong>
        <p>Contains 21% elemental calcium. Absorbed independently of stomach acid — ideal for older adults with reduced stomach acid production. Better tolerated with less GI distress. Can be taken with or without food. Preferred by gastroenterologists.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Tricalcium Phosphate</strong>
        <p>Contains 38% elemental calcium. A commonly used form in gummy supplements due to favorable formulation characteristics. Similar absorption profile to calcium carbonate. Also provides phosphorus, another bone-building mineral.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Vitamin D3 Synergy</strong>
        <p>Without vitamin D, you absorb only 10-15% of dietary calcium. With adequate vitamin D (600-2,000 IU daily), absorption increases to 30-40%. Always choose calcium gummies that include vitamin D3 for meaningful bone health benefits.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2015 meta-analysis published in the <em>BMJ</em> examined 33 randomized trials and found that <strong>calcium plus vitamin D supplementation reduced total fracture risk by 15%</strong> and hip fracture risk by 30% — but only at calcium doses of <strong>1,000mg or more daily</strong> combined with at least 800 IU vitamin D. Supplements providing less than these thresholds showed no significant fracture reduction.</p>
      <cite>BMJ, 2015 — 33 randomized trials, 51,145 participants</cite>
    </div>

