    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Calcium Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do calcium gummies actually work for bone health?</summary>
      <p>Calcium gummies support bone health when they deliver adequate elemental calcium with vitamin D3. Most provide 200-500mg per serving — meaningful supplementation, but not a complete daily dose. A 2015 BMJ meta-analysis found calcium + D supplementation reduced fracture risk by 15% at doses of 1,000mg+ calcium daily. Gummies work best alongside dietary calcium sources.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between calcium citrate and calcium carbonate?</summary>
      <p>Calcium carbonate contains 40% elemental calcium and requires stomach acid for absorption (take with food). Calcium citrate contains 21% elemental calcium but absorbs independently of stomach acid — better for older adults with reduced acid production. Citrate also causes less bloating and constipation. Most gummies use tricalcium phosphate, which has moderate absorption characteristics.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much calcium do I need per day?</summary>
      <p>1,000mg for adults ages 19-50, 1,200mg for women 51+ and men 71+, 1,300mg for adolescents. Most adults consume 700-900mg through food. A 200-500mg gummy bridges the gap. Do not take more than 500mg at once — split doses improve absorption significantly.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take calcium with vitamin D?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Without vitamin D, you absorb only 10-15% of dietary calcium. With adequate D (600-2,000 IU daily), absorption increases to 30-40%. Choose calcium gummies that include D3. If yours does not contain D, take a separate vitamin D3 supplement.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can calcium gummies cause kidney stones?</summary>
      <p>Excessive supplemental calcium (above 2,000mg total daily) may increase kidney stone risk in some individuals. However, adequate dietary calcium actually reduces stone risk by binding gut oxalate. Do not exceed 500-600mg supplemental calcium daily, take with meals, and stay hydrated. Consult your physician if you have a history of calcium oxalate stones.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why are calcium gummies lower dose than pills?</summary>
      <p>Calcium is a bulky mineral. Delivering 500mg in gummy form is already challenging — higher doses would make gummies impractically large or require 4-6 per serving. This is why calcium gummies are best used as a dietary supplement rather than a sole calcium source. Combine with calcium-rich foods for optimal intake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take calcium gummies?</summary>
      <p>With food, especially if using calcium carbonate. Split doses of 500mg or less absorb better than single large doses. Separate calcium and iron supplements by at least 2 hours — calcium inhibits iron absorption by up to 50%. Evening supplementation may support overnight bone remodeling.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are calcium gummies safe for children?</summary>
      <p>Age-appropriate calcium gummies are safe when taken as directed. Children 4-8 need 1,000mg daily; adolescents need 1,300mg. Most children get adequate calcium from dairy. Lactose-intolerant or dairy-free children may benefit from supplementation. Store out of reach to prevent overconsumption.</p>
    </details>

